Is it possible to regulate systemic risks ?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely to occur, because at the end of the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many ways, particularly with regard to sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the origin of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Then, predict the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed and when there is no more credit available) is, and will certainly remain, beyond our analytical capacities.
Finally, crises are strongly nonlinear events that occur without precursors.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those least responsible.
If this pattern were to be repeated, it could undermine confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could signal excessive regulations, state re-regulation, and disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a crisis of the sovereign debts of advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can be translated into a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration in tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenses.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "tax packages" of advanced economies include non-discretionary counter-cyclical measures.
Unseen imbalances and systemic risks make fiscal policies that appear prudent not actually be so.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
Their revenues and expenses were largely determined by a property bubble linked to very high debt.
Extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is probably a typical example.
Finally, the only exit door is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant of the danger, able to identify the emergence of a systemic risk and take corrective measures quickly.
New detailed legislative frameworks, emphasizing capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits to the size of financial institutions, consumer protection and resolution mechanisms, are soon to be adopted.
Hoping that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will in no way solve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and foretelling instability.
In addition to and in complement to new legislative frameworks, a full-fledged system of surveillance of systemic risks is needed.
Certain politicians and leading analysts, however, believe that such a system, aiming to identify and curb systemic risks, is futile.
Risk dynamics models are incomplete and the global financial system is complex and constantly changing, making risk detection, according to them, either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If skeptics are right, we would then have to accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability and will not be able to predict it in advance.
We should also accept a more prudent fiscal policy than the one we thought necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making in conditions of uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists in rejecting a true proposition and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be asked in the following terms: in the context of detection and response to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the most probable high cost?
The adversaries of prudent surveillance of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable sign of potential growing instability.
Chercher un such sign is a waste of time.
The instability occurs instantaneously.
But this position seems fallacious.
During the 2008 crisis, for example, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
However, we must admit that these warnings were perhaps not sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the breaking point.
They were, however, undoubtedly signs.
The second position is that there are indeed precursors, but they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This point of view implies that AQF has a probable higher cost than RQV, because there are many positive elements that are false and/or the remedy is worse than the disease.
No doubt that there are costs associated with the AQF error.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so the overall negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, for my part.
There may be a deeper trend at play.
Whether it be in business or investments, choices are constantly made in conditions of uncertainty, and mistakes are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be the opposite, that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one thinks that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless one has good reasons to do so.
However, in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at least debatable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try the experiment, and give responsibility to a new institution, or an existing one, which has access to relevant information, has sharp analytical skills, both at the financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively shielded from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the system's financial ability to self-regulate.
